Source: OIE (World Organization for Animal Health) [edited

Foot and Mouth Disease (Type O) in The United Kingdom / Great Britain
----------------------------------------
Extract from a fax received 21 Feb 2001 from Dr. J.M. Scudamore, Chief
Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food [MAFF,
London:
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 19 Feb 2001.
There were 2 outbreaks of FMD reported near Brentwood, Essex. The first
outbreak occurred in pigs in the lairage of an abattoir, the second in a
bull on a farm in the neighbourhood.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks: 32 bovines and 346 pigs.
No. of cases: 1 bovine and 28 pigs.
The origin of the virus is presently unknown.
Control measures: stamping-out policy; protection and surveillance zones
established around the outbreaks.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to the MAFF website in the UK, a third case of FMD in cattle has
been found. This case is within the previously declared infected area.
<http://www.maff.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/fmd/default.htm>
Another useful site is Mike Meredith's Pighealth webpage at
<http://www.pighealth.com/>
